04018nam a22005655i 9780774832861DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748328617 a10.59962/97807748328612doi  a(DE-B1597)661931  a(OCoLC)1018455231  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJF1061b.L694 2018 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a323.12231 aLowe-Walker, R.E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIntercultural Deliberation and the Politics of Minority Rights /cR.E. Lowe-Walker. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (236 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tThe Politics of Paradox: A Perennial Problem -- tCultural Difference and the Minority Rights Paradox -- tLiberal and Non-Liberal Worldviews -- tIntercultural Deliberation: An Innovative Approach -- tDeliberating Difference -- tPublic Reason -- tPolitical Identity -- tIntercultural Deliberation and the Minority Rights Paradox -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAchieving socio-political cohesion in a community with significant ethnic, cultural, and religious diversity is a difficult challenge in contemporary liberal democracies. In the quest for neutrality, public policies and institutions shaped by the needs of the majority can inadvertently marginalize minority interests. Minority groups must therefore translate their desire for cultural recognition into terms that, ironically, often minimize cultural difference. Intercultural Deliberation and the Politics of Minority Rights examines the relationship between this minority rights paradox and cultural difference, building a compelling case for an inclusive approach to navigating minority rights claims. R.E. Lowe-Walker’s intercultural deliberation is designed to mitigate the injustices imposed by majority norms. Instead of asking what the liberal state can tolerate, she asks how our understanding of difference affects our interpretation of minority claims, shifting the focus from how to limit difference toward inclusive deliberations. This important work thus serves as a measure of social justice and a vehicle for social change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDeliberative democracy. 0aMinoritiesxCivil rights. 0aMinorities-Civil rights. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311141792940uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483286140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774832861423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774832861/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-141792-9  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles